# SentinelPay: Core Banking Engine 🚀
SentinelPay is a robust, Spring Boot-based backend engine designed to handle core financial operations including user onboarding, real-time transfers, and transaction auditing.

# 🛠 Tech Stack
Java 17 (Open JDK)

Spring Boot 3.x

Spring Data JPA (Hibernate)

MySQL (Relational Database)

Lombok (Boilerplate reduction)

# 🏗 System Architecture
The system follows a standard N-Tier architecture to ensure scalability and separation of concerns.

Controller Layer: Handles RESTful endpoints and request validation.

Service Layer: Manages business logic (e.g., ensuring atomic transfers and automatic account generation).

Repository Layer: Direct communication with MySQL using JPA.

Audit Trail: Every movement of funds is logged into a dedicated transactions table with unique UUID references.

# 🚦 Features
Automated Onboarding: Creating a user automatically generates a 10-digit NUBAN-style account number and a linked wallet.

Atomic Transfers: Uses @Transactional to ensure data consistency; money never disappears during a failed operation.

Concurrency Control: (Optional mention) Managed balance updates using BigDecimal for financial precision.

Global Error Handling: Professional JSON error responses for "Insufficient Funds" or "Account Not Found" scenarios.

# 🔌 API Documentation
1. User Registration
Endpoint: POST /api/wallets/register

Body:

JSON
{
    "fullName": "Abolarin Israel",
    "email": "israel@example.com",
    "password": "secure_password"
}
2. Fund Transfer
Endpoint: POST /api/wallets/transfer

Body:

JSON
{
    "senderAccountNumber": "1234567890",
    "receiverAccountNumber": "0987654321",
    "amount": 500.50
}
3. Transaction History
Endpoint: GET /api/wallets/{accountNumber}/history

4. Balance Inquiry
Endpoint: GET /api/wallets/{accountNumber}/balance

# 📦 Database Schema
The database consists of three primary tables:

users: Stores profile data and the primary account number.

wallets: Stores real-time balances linked to user IDs.

transactions: An immutable ledger of all historical transfers.

# 🚀 How to Run
Clone the repository.

Update src/main/resources/application.properties with your MySQL credentials.

Run mvn spring-boot:run or launch from IntelliJ.

The application will automatically create the tables on the first run.